pullRequest.body:
We add delaborators for the following notations, introduced in #20688:

- `‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô`, which denotes the `m`-dimensional simplex in the `n`-truncated simplex category.
- `X _‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô`, which denotes the `m`-th term of an `n`-truncated simplicial object `X`.
- `X ^‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô`, which denotes the `m`-th term of an `n`-truncated cosimplicial object `X`.

If `pp.proofs` is set to `true`, we also pretty-print the proof `p : m ‚â§ n` for all three notations as `‚¶ãm, p‚¶å‚Çô`, `X _‚¶ãm, p‚¶å‚Çô`, and `X ^‚¶ãm, p‚¶å‚Çô`, respectively.

Credit to @kmill for one piece of code and much metaprogramming inspiration.

The following test, taken from [`#17732`](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/17732/files#diff-40ab7cd5656f9da110091d345b5b90bc73d7183951a1a663c173a51a585acca2R24-R31), shows that our delaborator attempts to pretty-print some terms even when the truncation level cannot be subscripted. 

I'm not aware of a fix for this that would still allow pretty-printing things like `[m]‚Çô‚Çä‚ÇÅ`, but any suggestions would be appreciated. It also might not matter, as I can't think of any cases where the difference between  `[m]‚Çô` and `[m]n‚úù` would be all that confusing.

```lean
import Mathlib.AlgebraicTopology.SimplexCategory
open SimplexCategory.Truncated

variable (n : ‚Ñï) (m : ‚Ñï) (h : m ‚â§ n) (x) (hx : x = [m]‚Çô) (n : True)

/- The delaborator should ideally not fire here because the truncation level is now `n‚úù`,
which cannot be subscripted. -/
/-- info: hx : x = [m]n‚úù -/
#guard_msgs in #check hx
```

Edit: Fixed in commits [5d41e60](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/20719/commits/5d41e60645ca700057a63336ef77d406ae438b77) and [f4d15c3](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/20719/commits/f4d15c31717976734ae09c6685d3b598659eb0bf).

I remember this being discussed elsewhere, but can you remind me why `decide` and `assumption` are needed here?

They are not needed (in that they don't solve any goals that aren't solved by `omega`), but I decided to keep them after some rudimentary benchmarking. Most of the goals solved by `trunc` can be solved by `decide` or `assumption`, and it is also nicer to carry around a single hypothesis rather than an omega proof.

That being said, I am happy to replace this with a simple `dsimp only [SimplexCategory.len_mk]; omega`.

In fact, can you use `get_elem_tactic`? If that works well for your applications, that is probably the most robust with respect to future changes in tactics. But otherwise just `omega` is best, I think.
`get_elem_tactic` was a perfect replacement for `trunc`, thanks!
Actually, `get_elem_tactic` turned out to be slightly less effective than `omega` in some cases. I have restored the `trunc` tactic, but it just delegates to `omega` now.
Could I encourage moving this to a separate file, perhaps even `Mathlib/Tactics/AlgebraicTopology/SimplexCategory.lean`?
Please add cross-references to the other macro/delaborator, and make sure both clearly describe their scope.

Really? I wish we wouldn't do this. This is notation for its own sake. I won't block this PR; you can do it if you want, but personally I think this is like blinking scrolling marquees on a 90s webpage...

To be clear, I have no particular attachment to this notation. I'm happy to change it if that's what we want to do.

However, I don't think this test is indicative of how the notation will actually be used. I expect that the vast majority of the time the truncation level (which is subscripted) will be a numeric literal or an extremely simple expression, perhaps as complex as `n + 1`.

@kim-em I believe I have addressed your other concerns above, but please let me know if you would prefer that we consider alternatives to the notations defined here. I am happy to start such a discussion on zulip.
This feels like a reason to not do this, rather than to have tests that guard the broken behaviour!

Similar to my comment above, I think this test exists to make sure that the delaborator doesn't create any confusion in extreme cases, but I don't actually expect these cases to arise very often in practice.

If we expect to be regularly using arbitrary expressions for the truncation level, then we should definitely change the notation.
This belongs in the same file as the subscript notation (or at least, next to it)

Currently, this `SimplexCategory.Truncated.Meta.subscript` function is used in three different notations: `‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô` (defined in this file) as well as `X _‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô` and `X ^‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô` (defined in `SimplicialObject/Basic.lean`).

Would you suggest moving it to somewhere more generic, or is it fine to be defined in the same place as the first of these three notations? I can also add a reference to this function from the two delaborators in `SimplicialObject/Basic.lean`.

The test should match the input here:
```suggestion
/-- info: ‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô ‚Çä ‚ÇÅ : CategoryTheory.FullSubcategory fun a => a.len ‚â§ n + 1 -/
#guard_msgs in #check ‚¶ãm‚¶å‚Çô ‚Çä ‚ÇÅ
```
If the spaces aren't in fact legal in the notation, then the delaborator should not emit them.
